# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1804-united-states-presidential-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Portions of dialogue and some lyrics were taken directly from the letters and memoirs of the actual participants of the Second Continental Congress.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] John Adams, representing Massachusetts in the Second Continental Congress in Philadelphia, laments the body's refusal to debate his motion to declare the colonies' independence from Great Britain and instead to discuss more trivial matters.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Disliked by most of his fellow Congressmen, he frequently seeks advice and comfort from his wife, Abigail.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Benjamin Franklin of Pennsylvania, one of the few who enjoys Adams' company due mainly to their shared dream of independence, suggests someone else propose the independence resolution.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Richard Henry Lee of Virginia eagerly agrees, and he rides home to get authorization from the state legislature to do so.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Lee returns, proposes the resolution and, over the objections of John Dickinson of Pennsylvania, leader of the Conservative faction seeking reconciliation with Britain, Congress agrees to debate the question, which becomes heated as tempers flare.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Caesar Rodney of Delaware, suffering from cancer, collapses and is forced to leave during the debate, depriving Adams of Delaware's vote.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] A new delegation from New Jersey arrives and votes in favor of independence (Franklin receives word that his son William, the Royal Governor of New Jersey, has been arrested).
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Seeking to kill the motion, Dickinson successfully moves that an independence vote be unanimous on the grounds that "no colony be torn away from its mother country without its own consent." To salvage the motion, Adams asks for a postponement to draft a declaration of grievances.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] President of the Congress, John Hancock, breaks the tie vote in favor of a declaration and appoints Adams, Franklin, Roger Sherman of Connecticut, Robert Livingston of New York, and Thomas Jefferson of Virginia to a committee to write it.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Despite his determination to go home to his wife, Martha, Jefferson reluctantly agrees to be the primary writer.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] After a full week passes without Jefferson's being able to complete the task, Adams summons Martha to Philadelphia; Martha charms both Adams and Franklin, and Jefferson finishes the draft.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] To convince Samuel Chase of Maryland to support independence, Adams agrees to accept General George Washington's plea to visit the army encampment in New Brunswick, New Jersey, taking Franklin and Chase with him.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] After the members return to their lodgings, a young military courier arrives and sadly relates to Congressional custodian Andrew McNair how his two best friends were killed in battle at Lexington.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] After Adams and Franklin return from New Jersey, the Declaration is read to the full Congress, which begins accepting many amendments.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Jefferson agrees to almost all of the changes, except striking language referring to King George as a "tyrant" and objecting to slavery.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Edward Rutledge of South Carolina leads the Southern members in walking out in protest just as Chase returns with Maryland's vote supporting independence.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Frustrated at Adams's refusal to compromise, Franklin tells him that to achieve the primary goal of independence Adams must accept that those with opinions contrary to his will be part of their new nation.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Badly shaken, Adams again seeks counsel from Abigail, and thanks to a delivery of much-needed saltpeter from her and the delegate from Georgia's sudden decision to support independence, Adams finds the strength and will to continue.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] On the day of the vote (July 2, 1776), Adams and Jefferson agree to drop the slavery provision, and Rutledge and the other Southern states vote for independence.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] With Delaware divided, Rodney is brought back to support independence by majority vote of its three representatives.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Eventually, all states vote for independence except divided Pennsylvania and New York, whose remaining representative, Lewis Morris, has abstained throughout the proceedings.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] When Dickinson rises to vote against the proposal, Franklin moves that the Pennsylvania delegation be polled: he votes for independence and Dickinson votes against it, leaving the question up to James Wilson.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Not wanting to be remembered for casting the decisive vote against American independence, Wilson votes in favor.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Dickinson resigns from Congress and vows to join the army to support the fight against the British, even though he believes it to be futile.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] As the members prepare to sign the Declaration of Independence on July 4, 1776, Morris receives word that his estates have been destroyed and his family moved to safety.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Despite not being authorized, Morris signs anyway.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] As McNair tolls the building's bell, one member per state signs, establishing the United States of America.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] An asterisk (*) indicates an actor or actress who was also in the original Broadway cast.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] An original motion picture soundtrack album was released in 1972 by Columbia Records on vinyl LP records.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] It contains all the musical numbers, with the exception of "Cool, Cool Considerate Men" and "Compliments".
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The soundtrack also contains the edited versions of some of the musical numbers that were presented in full on the laserdisc and DVD releases.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Although the Original Broadway Cast recording was released on CD in 1992, the film soundtrack remains unavailable in any digital format as of 2026.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Warner bought the film rights to the musical for $1.25 million.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Many members of the original Broadway cast, including William Daniels, Ken Howard, John Cullum, and Howard da Silva, reprised their roles for the film.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Ralston Hill, Ron Holgate, David Ford, Charles Rule and others repeated their roles from the Broadway production, marking their only appearances in feature film.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] This was a decision Warner made himself after feeling he made a mistake by turning down Julie Andrews for the 1964 film adaptation of *My Fair Lady* in favor of Audrey Hepburn.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Exteriors were filmed at the Warner Ranch in Burbank, California, the former Columbia Pictures backlot, where they built an entire street of Colonial Philadelphia.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Most of the Colonial sets were destroyed by a fire in the mid-1970s.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The water fountain seen during the musical number "The Lees of Old Virginia", with Ben Franklin, John Adams, and Richard Henry Lee, became known to television viewers as the fountain seen during the beginning credits of the TV series *Friends*.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] This fountain still exists directly across the street from the *Bewitched* and *I Dream of Jeannie* houses.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Interiors were shot at the old Columbia studio on Gower Street in Hollywood.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] *1776* was among the final films shot at Gower Studios before the Warner/Columbia merger in 1971.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] "Cool, Cool, Considerate Men" was cut from the film prior to its release and not included on the soundtrack recording nor on the first VHS tapes and laserdiscs.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The *Los Angeles Times* stated "The song 'Cool, Cool, Considerate Men' depicts Revolutionary War–era conservatives as power-hungry wheedlers focused on maintaining wealth." According to Jack L.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Warner, the film's producer and a friend of President Richard Nixon, Nixon requested the song be removed.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Warner's attempt to comply with Nixon's demands had initially been rebuffed by director Hunt during production, only for the song to be removed in post-production while Hunt was on vacation.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Warner also wanted the original negative of the song shredded, but the film's editor kept it in storage unaltered.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] (The footage, some of physically poor quality, was restored for the DVD and Blu-Ray releases.) Trailers had already been released in theaters with the "Considerate Men" number as its centerpiece; Warner had those trailers pulled and re-edited.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] In a 2015 interview, Hunt mentioned that Warner, on his deathbed in 1978, told a friend that he regretted editing the scene, believing he had ruined the film's structure as a result.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] It was only decades later that the song was restored to the film.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] When the Broadway musical was about to be presented to Nixon at the White House in 1970, before the film was made, his staff pressed the producers to cut the song then; their request was denied.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Some of the dialogue was taken from words written, often years or even decades later, by the actual people involved, and rearranged for dramatic effect.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The film particularly omits the views of the mid-Atlantic Quaker population, represented by Dickinson.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] A supposed physical fight between Dickinson and Adams is portrayed, in which Dickinson calls Adams a "lawyer" as an epithet, despite the fact that Dickinson was a lawyer himself.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Despite the film's inclusion of Martha Jefferson and Abigail Adams, Dickinson's wife, Mary Norris Dickinson, was the only spouse actually present in Philadelphia during the convention.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] (Franklin's common-law wife, Deborah Read, had died a year or so earlier.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Another departure from history is that the separation from Great Britain was accomplished in two steps: the actual vote for independence came on July 2 with the approval of Lee's resolution of independence.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The wording of the Declaration of Independence—the statement to the world as to the reasons necessitating the split—was then debated for three days before being approved on July 4.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The vote for independence did not hinge on passages being removed from the Declaration, since Congress had already voted in favor of independence.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] For the sake of drama, the play's authors combined the two events.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] In addition, some historians believe the Declaration was not signed on July 4, but on August 2, 1776.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Others note that the final copy of the document was signed by the delegates over several weeks and months, commencing in July and not completed until as late as September.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The Liberty Bell in *1776* is shown being rung as the delegates were signing the Declaration on July 4; however, Independence Hall's wooden steeple was structurally unstable, and the Liberty Bell was silent, having been lowered into the upper chamber of the brick tower.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] A smaller bell, used to toll the hours, may have rung on July 8, for the public reading of the Declaration.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Many characters in *1776* differ from their historical counterparts.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Central to the drama is the depiction of John Adams as "obnoxious and disliked." According to biographer David McCullough, Adams was one of the most respected members of Congress in 1776.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Adams's often-quoted description of himself in Congress as "obnoxious, suspected, and unpopular" is from a letter written 46 years later in 1822, after his unpopular presidency had likely colored his view of the past.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] According to McCullough, no delegate described Adams as obnoxious in 1776.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Historian Garry Wills earlier made a similar argument, writing that "historians relay John Adams's memories without sufficient skepticism", and that it was Dickinson, not Adams, who was advocating an unpopular position in 1776.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The Committee of Five appointed to write the Declaration of Independence were: Franklin, age 70 (Howard da Silva was 62 at the time of filming in 1971); Roger Sherman, 55 (Rex Robbins was 36); Adams, 41 (Daniels was 44); Jefferson, 33 (Ken Howard was 27); and Livingston, 29 (John Myhers was 49).
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Adams" say Livingston claims to have "been presented with a new son by the noble stork" to avoid writing the declaration; no such son ever existed.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] For practical and dramatic purposes, only 20 of the over 50 members of Congress present at the time are portrayed.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] This version of John Adams is, in part, a composite character, combining the real Adams with his cousin Samuel Adams, who was in Congress at the time but is mentioned as being absent in the script.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Although the play depicts Delaware's Caesar Rodney as an elderly man near death from skin cancer (which would eventually kill him), he was just 47 years old at the time and continued to be very active in the Revolution after signing the Declaration.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] He was not absent from the voting because of health; however, the play is accurate in having him arrive "in the nick of time", having ridden 80 miles (130 km) the night before (an event depicted on Delaware's 1999 State Quarter) unaided, instead of with the help of another delegate.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Further, Richard Henry Lee announces that he is returning to Virginia to serve as governor.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] He was never governor (it was Lee's ally Patrick Henry who assumed the post at that time); his cousin Henry Lee (who is anachronistically called "General 'Lighthorse' Harry Lee", a rank and nickname earned later) did eventually become governor (and the father of Confederate general Robert E.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] John Adams was also depicted as disliking Richard Henry Lee, but according to McCullough, Adams expressed nothing but "respect and admiration for the tall, masterly Virginian." He did dislike Benjamin Franklin, contrary to what was portrayed.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Martha Jefferson never traveled to Philadelphia to be with her husband; she was extremely ill during the summer of 1776, having just endured a miscarriage.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The play's authors invented the scene "to show something of the young Jefferson's life without destroying the unity of setting." Martha is also depicted as dancing a galop or polka with Franklin and Adams, dances not introduced until the 1800s.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The real Martha Jefferson would have been seated playing the early piano Thomas purchased for her, accompanying him as he played violin.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The film, like its stage counterpart, misidentifies John Morton, the deciding vote and a soft-spoken judge who only votes for the resolution to avoid being infamous for killing it, as James Wilson.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The real Wilson, though he had previously studied under Dickinson earlier in his career, had by 1776 become one of the most outspoken advocates for independence, and would only later become a judge on the Supreme Court.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] His patrician WASP accent in the film is misleading, since Wilson was a Scottish immigrant whose parents were farmers, while Morton's family was from Finland.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The quote attributed to Edmund Burke by Dr.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Lyman Hall in a key scene with Adams is a paraphrase of a real quote by Burke.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The song "Cool Considerate Men" is anachronistic; the terms "right" and "left" in politics were not in use until the French Revolution of 1789.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] John Dickinson, who is portrayed as an antagonist here, was motivated mainly by his Quaker roots and his respect for the British Constitution, having lived in England for 3 years in the 1750s.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] He was no wealthier than some members of the pro-Independence faction, and freed his slaves in 1777.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Thomas Jefferson wrote that "his name will be consecrated in history as one of the great worthies of the revolution".
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The film also misses the objection some had to the Declaration's stated basis in "rights of Man" based in "natural law" derived from a supernatural being.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The Quaker-based population in the mid-Atlantic, represented by Dickinson, objected to this conception.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The musical also deviates from history in its portrayal of attitudes about slavery.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] In *1776*, after a dramatic debate over slavery, the southern delegates walk out in protest of the Declaration's denunciation of the slave trade, and only support independence when that language was removed from the Declaration.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The walkout is fictional, as the debate over the wording of the declaration took place after the vote for independence on July 2, and apparently most delegates, northern and southern, supported the deletion of the clause.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The musical depicts Edward Rutledge as the leader of the opposition to an anti-slavery clause in Jefferson's original draft of the Declaration.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] However, while it is known that, according to Jefferson, the clause was opposed by South Carolina and Georgia, plus unspecified "northern brethren", that is all that is known about opposition to the clause.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Rutledge was a delegate from South Carolina, but there is no historical evidence that he played any part—much less a leadership role—in the opposition to the clause.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The musical does acknowledge the complexity of the Colonial attitudes toward slavery in the dramatic song "Molasses to Rum," sung by the Rutledge character, which illustrates the hypocrisy in northern condemnations of slavery since northerners profited from the triangle trade.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The musical depicts Franklin as claiming that he is the founder of the first abolitionist organization in the New World; the real Franklin did not become an abolitionist until after the American Revolution, becoming president of the Pennsylvania Abolition Society in 1785.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] It was actually Dickinson who freed his slaves in 1776, conditionally at first, and fully by 1787 when the Constitution was ratified.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] In both the play and the film, John Adams sarcastically predicts that Benjamin Franklin will receive from posterity too great a share of credit for the Revolution.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] "Franklin smote the ground and out sprang—George Washington.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] James Wilson is portrayed as subordinating himself to Dickinson's opposition to independence, only changing his vote so that he would not be remembered unfavorably.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] In fact, Wilson was considered one of the leading thinkers behind the American cause, consistently supporting and arguing for independence, although he would not cast his vote until his district had been caucused.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The formula John Adams gives Abigail for making saltpeter—"By treating sodium nitrate with potassium chloride, of course!"—refers to various chemicals by their modern names, instead of the names used in the 1770s.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] A more historically accurate version might be "treating soda niter with potash." More accurate still would have been a detailed description of the process, involving ingredients such as manure or bat guano, but that probably would have been too long, and repulsive to audiences.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Abigail's request for pins in exchange is not frivolous.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Electroplating had not been invented yet: The common pin was subject to rusting and breakage, and so required replacement.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] At the time, pins were necessary for a wide range of crafts, creating garments and headgear (including wigs), making lace, ribbon and other trimmings and textiles.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] They also served the roles now played by paperclips and staples.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Women used them as closures or to anchor pieces of clothing.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] (Hooks and eyes existed, but like so many manufactured goods, they had to be imported.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The hook-and-eye industry was not established in the United States until the early 19th century.) The real Abigail, if dressed as in this scene in the film, would have supported the front lacing of her gown by using pins to fasten the fabric to the stiffened bodice beneath.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Vincent Canby of *The New York Times* observed, "The music is resolutely unmemorable.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The lyrics sound as if they'd been written by someone high on root beer, and the book is familiar history—compressed here, stretched there—that has been gagged up and paced to Broadway's not-inspiring standards.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Hunt's screen version of *1776* ... insists on being so entertaining and, at times, even moving, that you might as well stop resisting it.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] I've seen *1776* now four times and it may well be that the repetition has worn grey my true-blue patriotism.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The movie is a good technical copy but rather than adding to the original in any meaningful way it merely fills it out with the usual superfluity of second-hand screen work.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Peter Hunt has directed with a view to maximum expenditure of energy.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] There is absolutely no chance that anyone will go to sleep during *1776*.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Most of the actors were brought to the film from the hugely successful stage version and they all know how to milk a scene for full value." Carole Kass of the *Richmond Times-Dispatch* stated that "the film, even though the conclusion is historical knowledge, is still suspenseful.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] One cares very much about the individual delegates and their votes, opting from the theater seat for freedom.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The film is also a reminder that when it came to pitting the status quo against progress, Virginia was one of the first to vote for tomorrow.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] In Philadelphia, the film opened to significantly different reactions across two of its daily newspapers.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Collins of *The Philadelphia Inquirer* called the film "an affront because it trivializes a big subject without any redeeming satirical intent.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The Founding Fathers are not cut down to human size, they are reduced to subhuman dimensions.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] They are made into singing clowns whose boobish behavior somehow produces one of the most eloquent expressions of the human spirit ever to come from the hand of man." On the other hand, Joe Baltake of the *Philadelphia Daily News* called it "a pompous, roguish, disarmingly charming movie musical.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Its original freshness is retained largely because its 1969 Broadway ancestor never attained the household-word popularity of, say, *My Fair Lady* and *The Sound of Music*.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Its storyline still comes across as something delightfully novel, as does its spirited score.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Unlike other stage-to-screen adaptations, this 'new' entertainment is free of the usual telltale staleness. [...] Under director Peter Hunt's guidance, the off-beat material works surprisingly well in musical form.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] A heavy hand could have been disastrous.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] In fact, even with Hunt's light touch, "1776" occasionally gives way to a sluggish stuffiness.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Some forbearance is necessary for total enjoyment.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Sherman Edwards' unusual songs remain the work's high point, especially "The Egg," "He Plays His Violin," "Sit Down, John" and the haunting "Momma, Look Sharp." Technically, the film is visually enchanting—a giant kaleidoscope of sprawling sets, period costumes and gobs of color.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The production design is equalled only by the admirable ensemble acting.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The film got similarly mixed reviews in Chicago.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Roger Ebert of the *Chicago Sun-Times* gave *1776* two stars and declared, "This is an insult to the real men who were Adams, Jefferson, Franklin and the rest ...
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The performances trapped inside these roles, as you might expect, are fairly dreadful.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] There are good actors in the movie (especially William Daniels as Adams and Donald Madden as John Dickinson), but they're forced to strut and posture so much that you wonder if they ever scratched or spit or anything ...
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] I can hardly bear to remember the songs, much less discuss them.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The movie received generally positive reviews in the United Kingdom.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Alexander Walker of the *Evening Standard* said "it ought to be heavy going and yet the surprising thing is I didn't find it so.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The energy is infectious." He also stated that "since it was written Into the record, *1776* could hardly ignore the moment when the reference to the slave trade was shamefully, but conveniently, struck out of the Declaration of Independence in order to carry the vote.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Adams—a fine role for William Daniels." It was not without its detractors in England, however.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] I only wish I could say this fidelity to the original concept actually worked, but the fact is you have to keep pinching yourself to remember that you're watching movie.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] On Rotten Tomatoes, the film has a 68% score, based on 19 reviews, with an average rating of 7.1/10.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The film was the Christmas attraction at Radio City Music Hall in New York City and performed very well, grossing $1,743,978 in its first six weeks.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] It did not perform as well in its other opening engagements in Philadelphia, Boston and Washington.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] It returned to the Music Hall for two weeks starting June 3, 1976 in honor of the United States Bicentennial.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The film was nominated for the Golden Globe Award for Best Motion Picture – Musical or Comedy but lost to *Cabaret*.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] Harry Stradling Jr. was nominated for the Academy Award for Best Cinematography but lost to Geoffrey Unsworth for *Cabaret*.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The film was first released on videocassette, which runs 148 minutes, and on Laserdisc in the 1980s.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The Laserdisc version runs 180 minutes and is rated PG.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The DVD, issued in 2002 as a "Restored Director's Cut", runs 165 minutes.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] It trims up some scenes and contains previously unreleased scenes, including the "Cool, Cool Considerate Men" musical number and accompanying dialogue.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] However, it excludes the previously released Overture (heard on laserdisc but not in cinemas).
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] The film was released on Blu-ray from a 4K-master on June 2, 2015.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] It contains two commentaries: an all-new commentary, with director Hunt, Daniels and Howard, and also the DVD commentary with Hunt and Peter Stone only.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] With two versions: the prior "Director's Cut", and a further "extended cut" (167 minutes), the release also includes two deleted and alternative scenes with filmmaker commentary, screen tests, and original theatrical trailers.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-film] On May 31, 2022, Sony Pictures released a three-disc 50th anniversary Blu-ray.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] In 1972, it was made into a film adaptation, with eight of the original Broadway actors reprising their roles.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] It has received three New York revivals: on Broadway in 1997, an Encores! concert in 2016, and a 2022 Broadway production in which the racially diverse cast was entirely made up of people who identify as female, trans, or non-binary.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] In 1925, Rodgers and Hart wrote a Broadway musical about the American Revolution called *Dearest Enemy*.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] In 1950, another musical about the Revolution was presented on Broadway, titled *Arms and the Girl*, with music by Morton Gould, lyrics by Dorothy Fields, and book by Herbert Fields, Dorothy Fields and Rouben Mamoulian, the show's director.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Sherman Edwards, a jazz pianist and Brill Building pop songwriter who had decades prior had minor roles in Broadway musicals, began developing lyrics and libretto for a musical based on the signing of the Declaration of Independence.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Edwards recounted that "I wanted to show [the founding fathers] at their outermost limits.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] These men were the cream of their colonies. ...
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] They disagreed and fought with each other.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The first songs in the project were published and copyrighted by 1964.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Producer Stuart Ostrow recommended that librettist Peter Stone collaborate with Edwards on the book of the musical.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams, the outspoken delegate from Massachusetts, was chosen as the central character, and his quest to persuade all 13 colonies to vote for independence became the central conflict.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Stone confined nearly all of the action to Independence Hall and the debate among the delegates, and featuring two female characters, Abigail Adams and Martha Jefferson, in the musical.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] After tryouts in New Haven, Conn., and Washington, D.C., the show opened on Broadway at the 46th Street Theatre on March 16, 1969.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] On May 8, 1776, the Second Continental Congress, convening in Philadelphia at present-day Independence Hall, proceeds with its business.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] John Adams, the controversial delegate from Braintree, Massachusetts, is frustrated because Congress will not even debate his proposals on independence.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Later, Adams meets delegate Benjamin Franklin, an elderly lecherous scamp, who suggests that Adams should let another, more popular delegate propose a resolution on independence and summons the charismatic Richard Henry Lee of Stratford, Virginia.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Lee eagerly agrees to return to Virginia to procure an independence resolution from the Virginia House of Burgesses using his family's reputation and clout ("The Lees of Old Virginia").
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] As Congress is assembled, President John Hancock notes that the entire New Jersey delegation has been absent for quite some time.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] A gloomy dispatch from George Washington, commander of the Continental Army, arrives by courier and is read aloud by Secretary Charles Thomson.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Shortly thereafter, Richard Henry Lee returns, bearing a resolution for independence.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Elated, Adams seconds the motion to open debate on the resolution.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] John Dickinson of Pennsylvania, a conservative and royal apologist, immediately moves to table the debate.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The vote is close, but debate is ultimately approved, prompting Dickinson to denounce the desire for independence as an overreaction to petty squabbles with Great Britain.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The debate becomes more heated and personal, sparking a physical fight between Dickinson and Adams and causing Caesar Rodney to intervene; Rodney collapses from cancer.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Pro-independence Scotsman Thomas McKean escorts Rodney back to Delaware, leaving conservative George Read in control of Delaware's delegation.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Read quickly seconds Rutledge's motion to end the debate and vote on independence, knowing it is likely to fail.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] At this moment, the Reverend John Witherspoon arrives, announcing that New Jersey's legislature has deposed its royal governor, Franklin's estranged loyalist son, and has sent Witherspoon as the new delegate with explicit instruction to vote for independence.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams, now seeing a path to victory, pushes to proceed with the vote, since ties are broken by Hancock, an Adams ally who is also from Massachusetts.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Dickinson moves to require the vote for independence to be unanimous.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The vote ends in a tie, but Hancock unexpectedly votes in favor of unanimity, explaining that if the colonies are divided, the crown will pit the colonies against each other.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Knowing that Dickinson will quash the resolution if the vote proceeds immediately, Adams moves to postpone the vote to buy time to rally the needed support; he proposes that Congress draft a Declaration of Independence to build support abroad for the cause.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Again, the vote ties; this time, Hancock votes to postpone.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Before they adjourn, John Hancock appoints a committee of Adams, Franklin, Roger Sherman of Connecticut, Robert Livingston of New York, and Lee to draft the declaration.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Lee informs the Congress that he has been appointed Governor of Virginia and departs, never to be seen again; Adams nominates another Virginian, the resident meteorologist Thomas Jefferson, who wants no part of the task as he is returning home to see his wife after six months.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Jefferson is forced to accept the task after the other four explain why they cannot or should not ("But, Mr.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams sends for Jefferson's beloved wife Martha, reasoning that if Thomas cannot return to her, she can be summoned to him and potentially break his writer's block.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] When she arrives, she refuses to speak to Adams or Franklin and spends the night with her husband.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams, alone, again exchanges letters with his wife Abigail ("Yours, Yours, Yours").
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The next morning, Franklin and Adams again attempt to engage Martha in conversation; she speaks, but tersely, and talks of her courtship with Thomas ("He Plays the Violin").
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams is delighted to find that Jefferson has written something, but instead of work on the declaration, it is a mere note asking for him and Martha to be left alone.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] In June, with the Congress in what looks like a state of total lethargy, another grim dispatch from General Washington arrives, denouncing the Continental Army recruits as useless, undisciplined and outmatched, having fallen prey to numerous prostitutes at the camp in New Brunswick, New Jersey.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams, sensing that Washington is exaggerating the crisis in hopes of securing more money, convinces Samuel Chase of Maryland to go with him to New Brunswick to test Chase's fears that the Revolutionary War is doomed to end in defeat; Franklin, eager to see the prostitutes for himself, tags along.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The conservatives depart, leaving McNair, the courier (a Continental Army corporal from Watertown, Massachusetts), and a teenage "leather apron" (workman) alone in the chamber.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] As McNair begins a mock session as *president pro tempore*, he escorts the courier to Adams's seat; there, the courier and McNair discourage the leather apron from joining the Army as the courier recalls his friends' deaths at Lexington ("Momma Look Sharp").
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] As Congress reconvenes in Philadelphia, Jefferson is outside the chamber while Thomson reads the completed draft of the declaration to the Congress.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams and Franklin arrive, delighted: though the troops are indeed undisciplined, they showed exceptional shooting skill hunting waterfowl for dinner, and this convinced Chase to vote for independence.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] They congratulate Jefferson on his work, and Franklin compares the creation of this new country to the hatching of a bird, though they disagree on what kind ("The Egg").
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] On June 28, Hancock asks if there are any alterations to be offered to the Declaration of Independence.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Many delegates voice suggestions, additions or deletions.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Edward Rutledge of South Carolina objects in particular to a clause condemning the slave trade.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Rutledge leads a walk-out with the delegates from both Carolinas and Georgia, and the rest of the Congress follows.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams, who insists on including the slavery clause on principle that excluding it would make the Congress hypocrites, discusses the matter with Franklin, who tells Adams that he must accept some degree of compromise if he wants the independence resolution to pass.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams calls on Abigail in his mind to help him, and she reminds him of his commitment to the cause ("Compliments").
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Bolstered by her (and the arrival of a delivery of kegs of saltpeter he had previously requested from her), Adams recovers his energy and sends Franklin to try and win the support of Pennsylvania's James Wilson and Jefferson to talk to Rutledge.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Re-reading a dispatch from Washington, Adams, now alone, wonders "Is Anybody There?" Hall returns; after considering the words of Edmund Burke, he decides to buck his constituency's loyalist preference and use his own judgment to vote Yea for independence on Georgia's behalf.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Hancock calls for the vote on the Lee Resolution.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] At this moment, Rodney returns to Congress to assure that Delaware will vote in favor of independence.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Although Pennsylvania passes on their first call, the rest of the New England and Mid-Atlantic colonies vote in favor of independence except for New York, who reluctantly abstains.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] South Carolina, North Carolina and Georgia all vote "yea".
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] On Pennsylvania's second call, Dickinson is about to announce that his colony votes "nay" when Franklin requests that the delegation be polled.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Hancock proposes that no man be allowed to sit in Congress without signing the Declaration.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Dickinson resigns but pledges his loyalty to the new nation and says he will join the army and fight on its behalf, even as he hopes for eventual reconciliation with England.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams leads the Congress in a salute to Dickinson as he leaves the chamber.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The courier arrives with another dispatch from General Washington; on the eve of the British army's looming attack on New York, Washington remarks on the bravery of his outmatched band of misfit militia members.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Washington also notes that Lewis Morris's family estate has been completely destroyed but that the Morris family was rescued and his sons joined the Continental Army.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Morris, in response, announces "To hell with New York" and agrees to sign the Declaration.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] On July 4, McNair is sent to ring the Liberty Bell.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] It is heard ringing in the background as Thomson calls one delegate from each colony to sign the Declaration, establishing the United States of America.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The delegates freeze in position as the Liberty Bell rings to a fevered pitch.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] After out-of-town tryouts, the original Broadway production opened on Broadway on March 16, 1969, at the 46th Street Theatre (now the Richard Rodgers Theatre) and closed on February 13, 1972, after 1,217 performances.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] In its three-year run, it played in three different theatres: the 46th Street, the St.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] James Theatre (1970) and, finally, the Majestic Theatre (1971).
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The principal cast included William Daniels, Howard da Silva, Paul Hecht, Clifford David, Ronald Holgate, David Ford, Virginia Vestoff and Ken Howard.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Rex Everhart, who was da Silva's understudy, replaced him on the original Broadway cast album after da Silva suffered a mild heart attack, which required him to leave the show temporarily.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Betty Buckley made her Broadway debut as Martha Jefferson in the original stage production.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Clifford David left the production soon after opening.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] He was replaced as Rutledge by David Cryer who was in turn replaced by John Cullum who became one of the few Broadway replacements in history to recreate a role on film.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The musical toured for two years in the United States and was given a London production, opening on June 16, 1970, at the New Theatre.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The production starred Lewis Fiander as Adams, Vivienne Ross as Abigail Adams, Ronald Radd, Bernard Lloyd, David Kernan as Rutledge, John Quentin as Jefferson and Cheryl Kennedy as Martha Jefferson.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] An Australian production, also with Lewis Fiander, opened at Her Majesty's Theatre in Melbourne on 26 June 1971 and moved to the Theatre Royal in Sydney on 11 September 1971.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] City Center staged concert from March 30 to April 3, 2016.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The cast included MacIntyre Dixon, Ric Stoneback, and Kevin Ligon reprising their roles from the 1997 revival as Andrew McNair, Samuel Chase, and George Read respectively.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The production notably sported a racially diverse cast in light of the recent success of another musical about the Founding Fathers, *Hamilton*.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The musical was produced in Chicago, Illinois by Porchlight Music Theatre as part of their "Porchlight Revisits" series in November 2018.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Directed by Michael Weber, Music Directed by Jeremy Ramey, with Musical Staging by Michelle Lauto.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The team held a two-week workshop on Zoom in April 2020, but the production was postponed due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] In June 2021, A.R.T. announced that the production, now directed by Jeffrey L.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Page and Paulus, would begin performances at A.R.T. in May 2022.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The cast (many of whom were making their Broadway debuts) included Crystal Lucas-Perry (later Kristolyn Lloyd) as Adams, Patrena Murray as Franklin, Elizabeth A.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Davis as Jefferson, Allison Kaye Daniel as Abigail/Rev.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Hall, Carolee Carmello as Dickinson and Sara Porkalob as Rutledge.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] A two-part radio production adapted and directed by Martin Jarvis starring Alfred Molina as Benjamin Franklin, Ioan Gruffud as John Adams.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The musical was performed in April 2026 at the Paper Mill Playhouse in Millburn, New Jersey under the direction of Mark S.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Hoebee with musical staging by Nancy Renée Braun.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The cast starred Will Blum as John Adams, Michael Burrell as Thomas Jefferson, and John Treacy Egan as Benjamin Franklin.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] In the 2022 revival, the end of Act I is moved to after "He Plays the Violin".
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] According to Peter Stone, Scene Three of *1776* holds the record for the longest time in a musical without a single note of music played or sung —– over thirty minutes pass between "The Lees of Old Virginia" and "But Mr.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] On the DVD commentary, Stone says that he experimented with adding various songs in this section, but nothing ever worked.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] During this scene, dubbed "Big Three" by cast members, musicians were allowed to leave the pit, reportedly the first time in Broadway history that they were permitted to do so in the middle of a show.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Stone also notes that people often told him that, because of the subject matter and the large amount of dialogue, *1776* should have been a conventional play rather than a musical.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Stone believes that the songs create a playful, irreverent tone that helps bring the historical characters to life.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The central departure from history is that the separation from Great Britain was accomplished in two steps: the actual vote for independence came on July 2 with the approval of Lee's resolution of independence.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The vote for independence did not hinge on some passages being removed from the Declaration, as implied in the play, since Congress had already voted in favor of independence before debating the Declaration.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] In addition, some historians believe that the Declaration was not signed on July 4, as shown in *1776*, but was instead signed on August 2, 1776.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The authors of *1776* had the delegates sign the Declaration on July 4 for dramatic reasons.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The pro-slavery and anti-black views espoused by Rutledge in the play bear similarities to his record, though Rutledge had supported the Lee Resolution and led the campaign to convince the other South Carolina delegates to support it.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Of the four principal characters, the musical also notably focuses on Jefferson's wife, Martha, and Adams' wife, Abigail, but omits Dickinson's wife, Mary Norris, who was actually in Philadelphia, unlike the other wives, and was an active correspondent with the other Founding Fathers.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Franklin's common-law wife, Deborah Read, was deceased at this point.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams's memories near the end of his life were, according to McCullough, likely distorted and affected by his troubled tenure as President in the late 1790s; no delegate described Adams as obnoxious in 1776.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] For practical and dramatic purposes, the play depicts only 19 of the more than 50 members of Congress who were present at the time.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The John Adams of the play is, in part, a composite character, combining the real Adams with his cousin Samuel Adams, who is noted in the play as being absent.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Although the play depicts Caesar Rodney as an elderly man near death from skin cancer (which would eventually kill him), he was just 47 at the time and continued to be very active in the Revolution after signing the Declaration.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] He was not absent from the voting because of health; however, the play is accurate in having him arrive "in the nick of time", having ridden 80 miles the night before (an event depicted on Delaware's 1999 State Quarter).
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Richard Henry Lee did not leave Congress to serve as Governor of Virginia, a post assumed at the time by Patrick Henry.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] In real life, he and his brother Francis were present to sign the Declaration, and his cousin "Light-Horse Harry" Lee, mentioned in "The Lees of Old Virginia" as a general, had only reached the rank of captain by 1776.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Adams had more admiration for the "tall, masterly Virginian" Lee than the play initially implies.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Martha Jefferson never traveled to Philadelphia to be with her husband.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] In fact, she was extremely ill during the summer of 1776, having just endured a miscarriage.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Jefferson rushed his work on the Declaration so he could return to Martha as soon as he could, and did so no later than August 1776, nine months before the birth of their short-lived son.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The song "Cool Considerate Men" is anachronistic, not only because of its quotation of the not-yet-written "The Star-Spangled Banner," but because the terms "right" and "left" in politics were not in use until the French Revolution of 1789.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Dickinson, who refused to sign the Declaration based on "rights of man" and "natural law", was seeking to avoid reopening issues from the English Civil Wars, including Oliver Cromwell's Puritan regime, and the Jacobitism cause.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] In 1689, these issues had been definitively resolved in the Glorious Revolution and the constitutionalization of the English Bill of Rights based in "rights and responsibilities of person"; the word "man" is not used except in the context of treason.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The last Jacobite rebellion, seeking to re-establish Catholicism and the religious concept of "natural law", had only just happened in 1745, however.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] None of this background of Dickinson's position is depicted.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Joseph Hewes is portrayed as having little to contribute to the debates, only to consistently yield to, and vote with, Rutledge.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] According to Adams's recollections several decades later, Hewes in fact was staunchly against independence but eventually and reluctantly conceded to popular support once reconciliation appeared to be impossible.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Thomas Jefferson is depicted as saying that he has resolved to free his slaves, something he did not do, except for a few slaves freed after his death 50 years later, due to the massive debt his estate incurred and the need to keep them on the books as collateral.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Many of Jefferson's slaves, particularly the Hemings family, were related by blood to Martha (and, after Martha's death, Jefferson is believed to have fathered others); he fought to keep the family united and treated them with privileges rare for slaves of the era.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Franklin claims that he is the founder of an abolitionist organization (the Pennsylvania Abolition Society); however, he had only joined said society in 1785, nine years after the declaration.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The musical misidentifies John Morton, the soft-spoken, experienced judge who cast the deciding vote in favor of independence solely to avoid the infamy of being the single vote that vetoed it, as James Wilson.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Wilson had been cautious about supporting independence at an earlier date, but he supported the resolution of independence when it came up for a vote.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Wilson was in fact one of the most outspoken political leaders of his era, as records tied to the later Constitutional Convention show, and would only become a judge after said Constitution was adopted.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The desire to not singlehandedly block the independence resolution was a joint decision of all the Pennsylvania delegates; in real life, Dickinson and another delegate agreed not to attend the July 2 vote to allow Franklin, Wilson and Morton to vote yes on Pennsylvania's behalf.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The phrase "We are about to brave the storm in a skiff made of paper", placed in the mouth of John Hancock, was actually stated by John Dickinson ("Others strenuously assert...we ought to brave the Storm in a Skiff made of Paper.") in his arguments against independence.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Franklin's comments about the eagle and the turkey in "The Egg" were based on comments he had made in a 1784 letter he had written criticizing the Society of the Cincinnati for, among other perceived wrongs, using an eagle as a symbol.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Furthermore, it was not Adams who chose the eagle as the *de facto* national bird, but instead secretary Charles Thomson.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The 2022 revival production includes an excerpt of Abigail Adams' March 1776 letter to John Adams, known for its "remember the ladies" statement for women's rights.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The 1972 film version of *1776* was produced by Jack L.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Warner with Hunt again directing and Stone writing the screenplay.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The film featured William Daniels as Adams, Ken Howard as Jefferson, Howard da Silva as Franklin, John Cullum as Edward Rutledge, Ron Holgate as Richard Henry Lee, and Virginia Vestoff as Abigail Adams, all of whom had performed their roles on Broadway.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The supporting cast was also mostly recruited from the Broadway production.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The principal exceptions were Donald Madden and Blythe Danner, who took over the roles of John Dickinson and Martha Jefferson.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] A Director's Cut of the original film has been released on DVD and Blu-ray.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Both the look and sound of the original film have been improved through modern technology.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Many cuts to the original film by the producer Jack Warner have been restored, including verses from the songs "Piddle Twiddle and Resolve" and "He Plays the Violin" and the entire "Cool, Cool, Considerate Men,” which Warner originally cut at the urging of President Nixon.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Nixon felt the scene presented conservatism in a negative light.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Musical underscoring has been removed from several scenes without songs in order to strengthen the focus on dialogue.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Bonus material includes commentary by Director Peter Hunt and by Peter Stone, the book/screenwriter.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] Among other topics, they discuss artistic liberties and anachronisms used to dramatize the events.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1776-musical] The musical *Hamilton* references the song "Sit Down, John!" in a lyric from the song, "The Adams Administration", in the lyric: "Sit down, John, you fat mother—[BLEEP]er." Lin-Manuel Miranda discovered the *1776* film in college and cites it as having paved the way for *Hamilton*.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from December 15, 1788 to January 7, 1789, under the new Constitution ratified in 1788.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] George Washington was unanimously elected for the first of his two terms as president and John Adams became the first vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] This was the only U.S. presidential election that spanned two calendar years without a contingent election and the first national presidential election in American history.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Under the Articles of Confederation, which were ratified in 1781, the United States had no head of state.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The executive function of government remained with the legislative similar to countries that use a parliamentary system.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Federal power, strictly limited, was reserved to the Congress of the Confederation whose "President of the United States in Congress Assembled" was also chair of the Committee of the States which aimed to fulfill a function similar to that of the modern Cabinet.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution created the offices of President and Vice President, fully separating these offices from Congress.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution established an Electoral College, based on each state's congressional representation, in which each elector would cast two votes for two candidates, a procedure modified in 1804 by the ratification of the Twelfth Amendment.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] States had varying methods for choosing presidential electors.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In five states, the state legislature chose electors.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The other six chose electors through some form involving a popular vote, though in only two states did the choice depend directly on a statewide vote.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The enormously popular Washington was distinguished as the former Commander of the Continental Army during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] After he agreed to come out of retirement, he was elected with ease unanimously; Washington did not select a running mate as that concept was not yet developed.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] No formal political parties existed, though an informally organized consistent difference of opinion had already manifested between Federalists and Anti-Federalists.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, the contest for the vice-presidency was open.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas Jefferson predicted that a popular Northern leader such as Governor John Hancock of Massachusetts or John Adams, a former minister to Great Britain who had represented Massachusetts in Congress, would be elected vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Anti-Federalists leaders such as Patrick Henry, who did not run, and George Clinton, who had opposed ratification of the Constitution, also represented potential choices.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] All 69 electors present cast one vote for Washington, making his election unanimous.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won 34 electoral votes and the vice presidency.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining 35 electoral votes were split among 10 candidates, including John Jay, who finished third with nine electoral votes.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Three states were ineligible to participate in the election: New York's legislature did not choose electors on time, and North Carolina and Rhode Island had not yet ratified the constitution.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was inaugurated in New York City on April 30, 1789, 57 days after the First Congress convened.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Both factions supported Washington for president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Limited, primitive political campaigning occurred in states and localities where swaying public opinion might have mattered.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, in Maryland, a state with a statewide popular vote, unofficial parties campaigned locally, advertising.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] No nomination process existed at the time of planning, and thus, the framers of the Constitution presumed that Washington would be elected unopposed.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Another uncertainty was the choice for the vice presidency, which contained no definite job description beyond being the president's designated successor and presiding over the Senate.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution stipulated that the position would be awarded to the runner-up in the presidential election.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Because Washington was from Virginia, then the largest state, many assumed that electors would choose a vice president from a northern state.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Minister to France Thomas Jefferson wrote that he considered John Adams and John Hancock, both from Massachusetts, to be the top contenders.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson suggested John Jay, John Rutledge, and Virginian James Madison as other possible candidates.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received 34 electoral votes, one short of a majority – because the Constitution did not require an outright majority in the Electoral College prior to ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to elect a runner-up as vice president, Adams was elected to that post.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, the states differed in their interpretations of this procedure and of the relevant portions of the new Constitution.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] New Hampshire and Massachusetts held a popular vote for their presidential electors alongside the elections for their representatives in the new Congress, on December 15 and December 18, respectively.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In these two states, the legislatures ultimately chose the electors based on the voting results on the appointed day, January 7.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In Delaware, Maryland, Pennsylvania, and Virginia, the electors were chosen directly by the popular vote on January 7.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In Connecticut, Georgia, and South Carolina, the electors were appointed by the legislature alone on January 7, while in New Jersey the governor and council selected them on that day.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The legislature in New York was unable to agree on a method for choosing the electors before January 7, and so the state could not appoint any electors.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Voter turnout comprised a low single-digit percentage of the adult population.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Though all states allowed some rudimentary form of popular vote, only six ratifying states allowed any form of popular vote specifically for presidential electors.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In most states only white men, and in many only those who owned property, could vote.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Free black men could vote in four Northern states, and women could vote in New Jersey until 1804.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In some states, there was a nominal religious test for voting.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, in Massachusetts and Connecticut, the Congregational Church was established, supported by taxes.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Voting was hampered by poor communications and infrastructure and the labor demands imposed by farming.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Two months passed after the election before the votes were counted and Washington was notified that he had been elected president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Washington spent eight days traveling from Virginia to New York for the inauguration.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Congress took twenty-eight days to assemble.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] As the electors were selected, politics intruded, and the process was not free of rumors and intrigue.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] For example, Hamilton aimed to ensure that Adams did not inadvertently tie Washington in the electoral vote.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Also, Federalists spread rumors that Anti-Federalists plotted to elect Richard Henry Lee or Patrick Henry president, with George Clinton as vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, Clinton received only three electoral votes.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Several respected sources, including the Biographical Directory of the United States Congress and the Political Graveyard, show this individual to be James Armstrong of Pennsylvania.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] However, primary sources, such as the Senate Journal, list only Armstrong's name, not his state.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Skeptics observe that Armstrong received his single vote from a Georgia elector.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Early presidential elections used a form of plurality block voting that preceded the widespread adoption of the general ticket.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Under this system, voters elected each member of the Electoral College individually; electors nominated by the same political party often received differing numbers of votes as a consequence of voter rolloff, split-ticket voting, or electoral fusion.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In most cases, this table calculates the popular vote of each state based on the votes for the leading Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors in each constituent county or township.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] In states where the electors were chosen from single-member districts, all votes for Federalist and Anti-Federalist electors are counted.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Most townships in New Hampshire are missing data for this election; the figure shown is the result for the leading Federalist elector statewide.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Because published compilations of the election results are missing labels for many electors, the estimate presented here is incomplete.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 69 participating electors, each cast one vote for Washington, who was elected president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Of the remaining candidates, only Adams, Jay, and Hancock received votes from more than one state; with 34 votes, Adams finished second behind only Washington, and by virtue of which fact was elected vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Control of the bicameral New York State Legislature was divided following ratification of the federal constitution, and lawmakers could not reach an agreement to appoint electors for the forthcoming presidential contest.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The fight to ratify the United States Constitution was still fresh in the memories of the legislators, and the Anti-Federalists were resentful for having been forced by events to accept the constitution without amendments.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] Bills to govern the selection of electors were proposed in each house and rejected by the other, leading to an impasse.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The deadlock still stood on January 7, 1789, the last day for electors to be chosen by the states, and New York thus failed to appoint the eight electors allocated to it by the constitution.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution, in Article II, Section 1, provided that the state legislatures should decide the manner in which their Electors were chosen.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 2 to December 5, 1792.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent President George Washington was elected to a second term by a unanimous vote in the electoral college, while John Adams was reelected as vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was essentially unopposed, but Adams faced a competitive re-election against Governor George Clinton of New York.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Electoral rules of the time required each presidential elector to cast two votes without distinguishing which was for president and which for vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The recipient of the most votes would then become president, and the runner-up vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican Party, which had organized in opposition to the policies of Secretary of the Treasury Alexander Hamilton, supported Clinton for the position of vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams, meanwhile, was backed by the Federalist Party in his bid for another term.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Neither party had fully organized, and partisan divisions had not yet solidified.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington received 132 electoral votes, one from each elector.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won 77 electoral votes, enough to win re-election.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton finished in third place with 50 electoral votes, taking his home state of New York as well as three Southern states.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Two other candidates won the five remaining electoral votes.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] This election was the first in which each of the original 13 states appointed electors, as did the newly added states of Kentucky and Vermont.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In 1792, presidential elections were still conducted according to the original method established under the U.S.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Under this system, each elector cast two votes: the candidate who received the greatest number of votes (so long as they won a majority) became president, while the runner-up became vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Twelfth Amendment would eventually replace this system, requiring electors to cast one vote for president and one vote for vice president, but this change did not take effect until 1804.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Because of this, it is difficult to use modern-day terminology to describe the relationship among the candidates in this election.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington is generally held by historians to have run unopposed.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Indeed, the incumbent president enjoyed bipartisan support and received one vote from every elector.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The choice for vice president was more divisive.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist Party threw its support behind the incumbent vice president, John Adams of Massachusetts, while the Democratic-Republican Party backed the candidacy of New York Governor George Clinton.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Because few doubted that Washington would receive the greatest number of votes, Adams and Clinton were effectively competing for the vice presidency; under the letter of the law, however, they were technically candidates for president competing against Washington.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Born out of the Anti-Federalist faction that had opposed the Constitution in 1788, the Democratic-Republican Party was the main opposition to the agenda of Treasury Secretary Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] They had no chance of unseating Washington, but hoped to win the vice presidency by defeating the incumbent, Adams.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Many Democratic-Republicans would have preferred to nominate Thomas Jefferson, their ideological leader and Washington's Secretary of State.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] However, this would have cost them the state of Virginia, as electors were not permitted to vote for two candidates from their home state and Washington was also a Virginian.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton, the Governor of New York and a former anti-Federalist leader, became the party's nominee after he won the backing of Jefferson and James Madison.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton was from an electorally important swing state, and he convinced party leaders that he would be a stronger candidate than another New Yorker, Senator Aaron Burr.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Democratic-Republican leaders met in Philadelphia in October 1792 and selected Clinton as the party's vice presidential candidate.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Madison was at first a Federalist until he opposed the establishment of Hamilton's First Bank of the United States in 1791.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] He formed the Democratic-Republican Party along with Anti-Federalist Thomas Jefferson in 1792.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The elections of 1792 were the first ones in the United States to be contested on anything resembling a partisan basis.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In most states, the congressional elections were recognized in some sense as a "struggle between the Treasury department and the republican interest," to use the words of Jefferson strategist John Beckley.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In New York, the race for governor was fought along these lines.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The candidates were Chief Justice John Jay, a Hamiltonian, and incumbent George Clinton, the party's vice presidential nominee.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Although Washington had been considering retiring, both sides encouraged him to remain in office to bridge factional differences.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was supported by practically all sides throughout his presidency and gained more popularity with the passage of the Bill of Rights.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] However, the Democratic-Republicans and the Federalists contested the vice-presidency, with incumbent John Adams as the Federalist nominee and George Clinton as the Democratic-Republican nominee.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists attacked Clinton for his past association with the anti-Federalists.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Congress counted the electoral results on February 13, 1793, with John Adams opening and reading the votes in his role as President of the Senate.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was re-elected unanimously, receiving one vote from each of the 132 participating electors.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received votes from 77 electors and Clinton 50; the four electors from Kentucky voted for Thomas Jefferson, and one South Carolina elector voted for Aaron Burr.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The distribution of the electoral vote between the four runners-up showed a high degree of party discipline, with only two electors voting contrary to the majority in their state.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received the support of New England, South Carolina, and the Mid-Atlantic states (excepting New York), while Clinton carried New York and most of the South.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Nine of the 15 states eligible to choose representatives to the electoral college did so by a vote of the state legislature; the remaining six employed some form of popular vote.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Of these, complete returns from Maryland, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, and Pennsylvania survive; surviving returns from Virginia are incomplete, and popular vote records from Kentucky are not known to exist.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Of the states with complete returns, only Pennsylvania saw real partisan competition; a Federalist electoral slate pledged to Washington and Adams was selected, although one elector voted for Washington and Clinton.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] At the time, party organizations were still in their infancy, and the partisan allegiance of the candidates was not always evident: it is therefore difficult to say whether the Pennsylvania vote for Clinton was an instance of a faithless elector, or an elector voting as pledged.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Elections in this period were vastly different from modern day presidential elections.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The actual presidential candidates were rarely mentioned on tickets and voters were voting for particular electors who were pledged to a particular candidate.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] There was sometimes confusion as to who the particular elector was actually pledged to.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Results are reported as the highest result for an elector for any given faction.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] For example, if three Federalist electors received 100, 50, and 25 votes, Federalist electors would be recorded as having 100 votes.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Confusion surrounding the way results are reported may lead to discrepancies between the sum of all state results and national results.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In Massachusetts, the best performing elector candidate for the Eastern District, Thomas Rice, was not selected by the Massachusetts General Court to be an elector.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Rice was a Federalist and his returns have been included into the state total below instead of the second best performing elector candidate.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The totals for Kentucky, Pennsylvania, and Virginia appear to be incomplete.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In several states candidates of unknown affiliation received votes.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The states chose 135 electors, out of whom 132 cast ballots.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] (Two electors from Maryland and one from Vermont were absent and did not vote.) As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Each of the participating electors cast one vote for Washington, who was elected president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The electors were split on their second choice: Adams received 77 votes to Clinton's 50, enough to secure a second-place finish behind Washington and the vice presidency.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 4 to December 7, 1796, when electors throughout the United States cast their ballots.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] It was the first contested American presidential election, the first presidential election in which political parties played a dominant role, and the only presidential election in which a president and vice president were elected from opposing tickets.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent vice president John Adams of the Federalist Party defeated former secretary of state Thomas Jefferson of the Democratic-Republican Party.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With incumbent president George Washington having refused a third term in office, the 1796 election became the first U.S. presidential election in which political parties competed for the presidency.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists coalesced behind Adams and the Democratic-Republicans supported Jefferson, but each party ran multiple candidates.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Under the electoral rules in place prior to the Twelfth Amendment, the members of the Electoral College each cast two votes, with no distinction made between electoral votes for president and electoral votes for vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The individual with the votes of a majority of electors became president, and the runner-up became vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If there was a tie for first place or no person won a majority, the House of Representatives would hold a contingent election.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Also, if there were a tie for second place, the vice presidency, the Senate would hold a contingent election to break the tie.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The campaign was a bitter one, with Federalists attempting to identify the Democratic-Republicans with the violence of the French Revolution and the Democratic-Republicans accusing the Federalists of favoring monarchism and aristocracy.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Republicans sought to associate Adams with the policies developed by fellow Federalist Alexander Hamilton during the Washington administration, which they declaimed were too much in favor of Great Britain and a centralized national government.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In foreign policy, Republicans denounced the Federalists over the Jay Treaty, which had established a temporary peace with Great Britain.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists attacked Jefferson's moral character, alleging he was an atheist and that he had been a coward during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams's supporters also accused Jefferson of being too pro-France; the accusation was underscored when the French ambassador embarrassed the Republicans by publicly backing Jefferson and attacking the Federalists right before the election.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Despite the hostility between their respective camps, neither Adams nor Jefferson actively campaigned for the presidency.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams was elected president with 71 electoral votes, one more than was needed for a majority.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] He won by sweeping the electoral votes of New England and winning votes from several other swing states, especially the states of the Mid-Atlantic region.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson received 68 electoral votes and was elected vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Former governor Thomas Pinckney of South Carolina, a Federalist, finished with 59 electoral votes, while Senator Aaron Burr, a Democratic-Republican from New York, won 30 electoral votes.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining 48 electoral votes were dispersed among nine other candidates.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Several electors cast one vote for a Federalist candidate and one for a Democratic-Republican.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With Washington retiring after two terms, both parties sought the presidency for the first time.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Before the ratification of the 12th Amendment in 1804, each elector was to vote for two persons but was not able to indicate which vote was for president and which for vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, the recipient of the most electoral votes would become president and the runner-up vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] As a result, both parties ran multiple candidates for president, in hopes of keeping one of their opponents from being the runner-up.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] These candidates were the equivalent of modern-day running mates, but under the law, they were all candidates for president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, both Adams and Jefferson were technically opposed by several members of their own parties.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The plan was for one of the electors to cast a vote for the main party nominee (Adams or Jefferson) and a candidate besides the primary running mate, thus ensuring that the main nominee would have one more vote than his running mate.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists' nominee was John Adams of Massachusetts, the incumbent vice president and a leading voice during the Revolutionary period.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Most Federalist leaders viewed Adams, who had twice been elected vice president, as Washington's natural heir.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams's main running mate was Thomas Pinckney, a former governor of South Carolina who had negotiated the Treaty of San Lorenzo with Spain.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney agreed to run after the first choice of many party leaders, former governor Patrick Henry of Virginia, declined.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Alexander Hamilton, who competed with Adams for leadership of the party, worked behind the scenes to elect Pinckney over Adams by convincing Jefferson electors from South Carolina to cast their second votes for Pinckney.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton did prefer Adams to Jefferson, and urged Federalist electors to cast their votes for Adams and Pinckney.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans united behind former secretary of state Thomas Jefferson, who had co-founded the party with James Madison and others in opposition to Hamilton's policies.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Congressional Democratic-Republicans sought to also unite behind one vice-presidential nominee.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With Jefferson's popularity strongest in the South, many party leaders wanted a Northern candidate as Jefferson's running mate.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Popular choices included Senator Pierce Butler of South Carolina and three New Yorkers: Senator Aaron Burr, Chancellor Robert R.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Livingston, and former governor George Clinton.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Democratic-Republican leaders met in June 1796 and agreed to support Jefferson for president and Burr for vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Tennessee was admitted into the United States after the 1792 election, increasing the Electoral College to 138 electors.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Under the system in place before the 1804 ratification of the Twelfth Amendment, electors were to cast votes for two persons for president; the runner-up in the presidential race was elected vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If no candidate won votes from a majority of the Electoral College, the House of Representatives would hold a contingent election to select the winner.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Each party intended to manipulate the results by having some of their electors cast one vote for the intended presidential candidate and one vote for someone besides the intended vice-presidential candidate, leaving their vice-presidential candidate a few votes shy of their presidential candidate.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] But all electoral votes were cast on the same day, and communications between states were extremely slow at that time, making it very difficult to coordinate which electors were to manipulate their vote for vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Additionally, there were rumors that Hamilton had coerced southern electors pledged to Jefferson to give their second vote to Pinckney in hope of electing him president instead of Adams.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Campaigning centered in the swing states of New York and Pennsylvania.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Adams and Jefferson won a combined 139 electoral votes from the 138 members of the Electoral College.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists swept every state north of the Mason–Dixon line except Pennsylvania, though one Pennsylvania elector voted for Adams.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans won the votes of most Southern electors, but the electors of Maryland and Delaware gave a majority of their votes to Federalist candidates, while North Carolina and Virginia each gave Adams one electoral vote.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Nationwide, most electors voted for Adams and a second Federalist or for Jefferson and a second Democratic-Republican, but there were several exceptions to this.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] One elector in Maryland voted for both Adams and Jefferson, and two electors cast votes for Washington, who had not campaigned and was not formally affiliated with either party.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney won the second votes from most of the electors who voted for Adams, but 21 electors from New England and Maryland cast their second votes for other candidates, including Chief Justice Oliver Ellsworth.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Those who voted for Jefferson were significantly less united in their second choice, though Burr won a plurality of the Jefferson electors.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] All eight electors in Pinckney's home state of South Carolina, as well as at least one Pennsylvania elector, cast their ballots for Jefferson and Pinckney.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In North Carolina, Jefferson won 11 votes, but the remaining 13 were spread among six different candidates from both parties.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In Virginia, most electors voted for Jefferson and Governor Samuel Adams of Massachusetts.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Congress counted the electoral results on February 8, 1797, with John Adams opening and reading the votes in his role as President of the Senate.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Although some contemporary newspapers contested the legal validity of Vermont's electoral votes, no objections against them were raised in congress.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The result was that Adams received 71 electoral votes, one more than required to be elected president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If any two of the three Adams electors in Pennsylvania, Virginia, and North Carolina had voted with the rest of their states, it would have flipped the election.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson received 68 votes, nine more than Pinckney, and was elected vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Burr finished in a distant fourth place with 30 votes.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Nine other candidates received the remaining 48 electoral votes.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] If Pinckney had won the second votes of all of the New England electors who voted for Adams, he would have been elected president over Adams and Jefferson.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 138 participating electors, 70 voted for Adams and some other candidate and 67 voted for Jefferson and some other candidate; one elector from Maryland voted for both Adams and Jefferson, bringing their respective totals to 71 and 68.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] With both parties' electors divided on their choice of a vice president, Jefferson finished second in the electoral vote ahead of Adams' intended running mate, Thomas Pinckney of South Carolina, making him vice president-elect.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Compiling reliable popular vote statistics for elections of the First Party System poses a challenge to historians.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Election procedures of the late 18th century differed greatly from those of later campaigns: rather than vote for a presidential candidate, voters chose from candidates running to represent their state in the electoral college.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Candidates for elector did not always advertise a party preference or even for whom they intended to vote; in some districts, candidates from the same party were in direct competition, while in others, inconsistent support for all candidates of a party led states to split their electoral votes.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] These conditions make it difficult or impossible to determine voter intent in some cases.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Moreover, some states' returns have not survived to the present day, meaning that national popular vote totals in this article are necessarily incomplete.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The table below calculates each state's popular vote by comparing the vote for the most popular Adams elector to that for the most popular Jefferson elector.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] In Massachusetts, the best performing elector candidates for the First Western and Second Middle Districts, Simon Larned and James Winthrop respectively, were not selected by the Massachusetts General Court to be electors.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Larned was a Democratic-Republican and Winthrop was a former Anti-Federalist.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The totals for Massachusetts and Virginia appear to be incomplete.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The following four years were the only time that the president and vice president were from different parties.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Calhoun were later elected president and vice-president as political opponents, but they were both Democratic-Republicans, and while Andrew Johnson, Abraham Lincoln's second vice-president, was a Democrat, Lincoln ran on a combined National Union Party ticket in 1864, not as a strict Republican.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] On January 6, 1797, Representative William L.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] Smith of South Carolina presented a resolution on the floor of the House of Representatives for an amendment to the Constitution by which the presidential electors would designate which candidate would be president and which vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] No action was taken on his proposal, setting the stage for the deadlocked election of 1800.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] This is also the first of only two elections so far in the life of the Republic which elected a presidential term of only 1,460 days rather than 1,461 days (the second was in 1896).
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] This is because of the Gregorian calendar rule that years ending in “00” but not divisible by 400, are not leap years.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The French foreign minister, Charles Delacroix, wrote that France "must raise up the [American] people and at the same time conceal the lever by which we do so...
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] The foreign intrigue France perpetrated was unsuccessful, as Adams won the election with an electoral vote count of 71–68.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1796-united-states-presidential-election] A significant factor in thwarting the French efforts was George Washington's Farewell Address, which condemned foreign meddling in America.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from October 31 to December 3, 1800.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first presidential election in U.S. history to be a rematch, the first election where an incumbent president lost re-election, leading to the first time in modern history where a national government changed hands peaceably following a free election.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Adams had narrowly defeated Jefferson in the 1796 election.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Under the rules of the electoral system in place before the 1804 ratification of the Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution, each member of the Electoral College cast two votes, with no distinction made between electoral votes for president and electoral votes for vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] As Jefferson received the second-most votes in 1796, he was elected vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In 1800, unlike in 1796, both parties formally nominated tickets.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans nominated a ticket consisting of Jefferson and Aaron Burr, while the Federalists nominated a ticket consisting of Adams and Charles Cotesworth Pinckney.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Each party formed a plan by which one of their respective electors would vote for a third candidate or abstain so that its preferred presidential candidate (Adams for the Federalists and Jefferson for the Democratic-Republicans) would win one more vote than the party's other nominee.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The chief political issues revolved around the fallout from the French Revolution and the Quasi-War.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists favored a strong central government and close relations with Great Britain.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans favored decentralization to the state governments, and the party attacked the taxes the Federalists imposed.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans also denounced the Alien and Sedition Acts, which the Federalists had passed to make it harder for immigrants to become citizens and to restrict statements critical of the federal government.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans were well organized at the state and local levels, while the Federalists were disorganized and suffered a bitter split between their two major leaders, Adams and Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] According to historian John Ferling, the jockeying for electoral votes, regional divisions, and the propaganda smear campaigns created by both parties made the election recognizably modern.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] At the end of a long and bitter campaign, Jefferson and Burr each won 73 electoral votes, Adams won 65, and Pinckney won 64.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists swept New England, the Democratic-Republicans dominated the South, and the parties split the Mid-Atlantic states of New York, New Jersey, and Pennsylvania.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans' assumption that one or more electors in Rhode Island, Vermont, New Jersey, Georgia, Kentucky, or Tennessee would vote for Jefferson and not Burr resulted in a tie, known as the Burr dilemma.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It necessitated a contingent election in the House of Representatives.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Under the terms laid out in the Constitution, the outgoing House of Representatives chose between Jefferson and Burr.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Burr was accused of campaigning for the presidency himself in the contingent election despite being a member of Jefferson's party.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Each state delegation cast one vote, and a victory in the contingent election required one candidate to win a majority of the state delegations.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Neither Burr nor Jefferson was able to win on the first 35 ballots of the contingent election, as most Federalist representatives backed Burr and all Democratic-Republican representatives backed Jefferson.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton favored Jefferson over Burr, and he convinced several Federalists to switch their support to Jefferson, giving Jefferson a victory on the 36th ballot.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson became the second consecutive incumbent vice president to be elected president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This is one of two presidential elections (along with the 1824 election) that have been decided in the House.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Both parties used congressional nominating caucuses to formally nominate tickets for the first time.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists nominated a ticket consisting of incumbent President John Adams of Massachusetts and Charles Cotesworth Pinckney of South Carolina.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney had fought in the American Revolutionary War and later served as the minister to France.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans nominated a ticket consisting of Vice President Thomas Jefferson of Virginia and former Senator Aaron Burr of New York.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson had been the runner-up in the previous election and had co-founded the party with James Madison and others, while Burr was popular in the electorally important state of New York.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] While the 1800 election was a re-match of the 1796 election, it ushered in a new type of American politics, a two-party republic and acrimonious campaigning behind the scenes and through the press.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] On top of this, the election pitted the "larger than life" Adams and Jefferson, who were formerly close allies turned political enemies.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The campaign was bitter and characterized by slander and personal attacks on both sides.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists spread rumors that the Democratic-Republicans were radical atheists who would ruin the country (based on the Democratic-Republican support for the French Revolution).
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In 1798, George Washington had complained "that you could as soon scrub the blackamoor white, as to change the principles of a professed Democrat; and that he will leave nothing unattempted to overturn the Government of this Country".
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Meanwhile, the Democratic-Republicans accused Federalists of subverting republican principles with the Alien and Sedition Acts.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] They also accused Federalists of favoring Britain in its war with France in order to promote aristocratic, anti-democratic values.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Ideology played a central role with a Jeffersonian "left" supporting the French Revolution, versus a Federalist "right" opposing it.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Adams was attacked by both the opposition Democratic-Republicans and a group of so-called "High Federalists" aligned with Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] "High Federalists" considered Adams too moderate and would have preferred the leadership of Alexander Hamilton instead.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton had apparently grown impatient with Adams and wanted a new president who was more receptive to his goals.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] During Washington's presidency, Hamilton had been able to influence the federal response to the Whiskey Rebellion (which threatened the government's power to tax citizens).
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] When Washington announced that he would not seek a third term, the Federalists and Adams regarded himself as next-in-line.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton appears to have hoped in 1796 that his influence within an Adams administration would be as great as or greater than in Washington's.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] By 1800, Hamilton had come to realize that Adams was too independent and thought the Federalist vice presidential candidate, Charles Cotesworth Pinckney of South Carolina, more suited to serving Hamilton's interests.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In his third sabotage attempt toward Adams, Hamilton quietly schemed to elect Pinckney to the presidency.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Given Pinckney's lack of political experience, he would have been expected to be open to Hamilton's influence.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, Hamilton's plan backfired and hurt the Federalist party, particularly after one of his letters, a scathing criticism of Adams that was fifty-four pages long, fell into the hands of a Democratic-Republican and soon after became public.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It embarrassed Adams and damaged Hamilton's efforts on behalf of Pinckney, not to mention speeding Hamilton's own political decline.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The contemporarily unorthodox public campaigning methods employed in 1800 were first employed by Jefferson's running mate and campaign manager, Aaron Burr, who is credited by some historians with inventing the modern electioneering process.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Yet, throughout this entire process, the candidates themselves were conspicuously missing from the campaigning, at least publicly, due to fears that they may otherwise be tagged as "demagogues".
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Even a visit John Adams made to Washington was made into a public point of contention.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Partisans on both sides sought any advantage they could find.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In several states, this included changing the process of selecting electors to ensure the desired result.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Georgia, Democratic-Republican legislators replaced the popular vote with selection by the state legislature.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Virginia, the Democratic-Republican-controlled legislature switched from electoral districts to a general ticket, a winner-take-all system.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Federalist legislators also switched methods, switching from districts and general tickets to legislature votes in Massachusetts and New Hampshire, respectively.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Pennsylvania, the General Assembly was split, with the Democratic-Republican-dominated House wishing to retain the general ticket and the Federalist-controlled Senate wishing to return to the district system, hoping to win at least some electoral votes.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Eventually, this deadlock was broken by a last-minute compromise between the chambers that gave the Democratic-Republican eight electors and the Federalists seven.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In New York, the rejection to change the selection method backfired on the Federalists.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In March 1800, two months before the assembly elections, the Democratic-Republicans attempted to pass a bill that would switch from a legislature vote to electoral districts, hoping they would secure at least a third of the state's seats.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists defeated the measure, believing that they would win control of both chambers and award all of the state's electoral votes to the Federalist nominees.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, in the April state elections, Aaron Burr's effective mobilization of the vote in New York City led to a reversal of the Federalist majority in the state legislature, providing crucial support for the Democratic-Republican ticket.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In response to the Federalist defeat, Hamilton attempted to get Governor John Jay to call a special session of the outgoing Federalist-dominated New York legislature.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton's plan was for the outgoing assembly to pass legislation that would establish the popular election of electors through electoral districts, a strategy almost certain to secure nine or ten of the twelve elector slots for the Federalists.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jay refused to participate in such an underhanded scheme.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist legislature in Connecticut did not change the method of voting but instead passed a "stand up" election law, mandating that all votes be cast publicly and orally, an intimidating procedure that ordinarily favored those in power.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] As election day neared, the election was too close to call.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The last state to vote, South Carolina, chose its electors on December 2, and would become key to determining the election.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The state elections in mid-October had produced an assembly that was about evenly divided between committed Federalists and Republicans, with 16 unaffiliated representatives who were all strongly pro-Jefferson.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Many of the elected Jeffersonians were also supporters of Pinckney, the revered native son of the state.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] If South Carolina's electors gave their votes to Jefferson and Pinckney, then Pinckney would place an electoral vote behind Jefferson, becoming the vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, Pinckney stayed loyal to the instructions of his party's caucus and was adamant that any elector who voted for him must also vote for Adams.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] With uncommitted legislators not willing to desert Jefferson and Pinckney unwilling to abandon Adams, the uncommitted legislators eventually reluctantly agreed to support Burr.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Under the United States Constitution as it then stood, each elector cast two votes, and the candidate with a majority of the votes was elected president, with the vice presidency going to the runner-up.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists therefore arranged for one of their Rhode Island electors to vote for John Jay instead of Charles Pinckney to prevent the election from resulting in a tie.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] A letter to Jefferson from Peter Freneau assured him that a member of the Republican delegation from South Carolina would vote for George Clinton instead of Aaron Burr and a report from Georgia indicated that two of its electors would deny Burr their votes.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] However, this information proved faulty.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Thus, all of the Democratic-Republican electors cast their votes for both Jefferson and Burr, 73 in all for each of them.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] According to a provision of the United States Constitution, a tie in a case of this type had to be resolved by the House of Representatives, with each state casting one vote.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the outgoing House, the Federalists had a majority of 60 seats to 46.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] When the electoral ballots were opened and counted on February 11, 1801, the certificate of election from Georgia was different than the others.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Georgia had sent the original oral ballot.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In 2004, David Fontana and Bruce Ackerman asserted that Georgia's certificate did not take the constitutionally mandated form of a "List of all the Persons voted for, and of the Number of Votes for each".
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] They claimed that Vice President Jefferson, who was presiding over the counting of electoral votes in his role as President of the Senate, immediately counted the votes from Georgia as votes for Jefferson and Burr, though they observed that "no objections were raised".
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney, and John Jay) in the House of Representatives.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] With these votes, the total number of votes for Jefferson and Burr was 73, which gave them a majority of the total, but they were tied.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Holly Brewer, a legal historian, argued that the counting of the Georgia ballot did not support Ackerman and Fontana's theory.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Brewer's arguments helped to influence Vice President Pence's decision to reject the theory that he had such powers, via Judge J.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson and Burr carried every state that had supported the Democratic-Republicans in 1796, made gains in Maryland, and picked up Burr's home state of New York.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the six states choosing electors by some form of popular vote, they won a landslide over Adams and Pinckney, polling 15,846 more votes than the Federalist ticket.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Adams made gains in Pennsylvania and North Carolina, but these votes were not enough to offset the Democratic-Republican gains elsewhere.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 155 counties and independent cities making returns, Jefferson and Burr won in 115 (74.19%), whereas the Adams ticket carried 40 (25.81%).
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This was the last time that Vermont voted for the Federalists and the last time a Federalist won electoral votes from Pennsylvania.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first of two elections contested between people who would at some point serve as vice president, the other being 1968.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Of the 16 states that took part in the 1800 election, six (Kentucky, Maryland, North Carolina, Rhode Island, Tennessee, and Virginia) used some kind of popular vote.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In Rhode Island and Virginia, voters elected their state's entire Electoral College delegation at large; Kentucky, Maryland, North Carolina, and Tennessee all used some variation of single-member districts.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the rest, electors were chosen by the state legislature.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Not until the 1836 presidential election would all states have direct popular selection of electors (except South Carolina, which had its state legislature vote for electors until 1868).
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Popular vote records for several states are incomplete, and the returns from Kentucky and Tennessee appear to have been lost; states did not print or issue electoral ballots, and most were issued by newspapers that supported a particular party or candidate.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Newspapers are also the main source of voting records in the early 19th century, and frontier states such as Tennessee had few in operation, without any known surviving examples.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Kentucky, Maryland, North Carolina, and Tennessee chose each of their electors from specially-drawn single-member districts, the results from which are as follows.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In February 1801, the members of the House of Representatives balloted as states to determine whether Jefferson or Burr would become president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] There were sixteen states, each with one vote; an absolute majority of nine was required for victory.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It was the outgoing House of Representatives, controlled by the Federalist Party, that was charged with electing the new president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson was the great enemy of the Federalists, and a faction of Federalist representatives tried to block him and elect Burr.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Most Federalists voted for Burr, giving Burr six of the eight states controlled by Federalists.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The seven delegations controlled by Democratic-Republicans all voted for Jefferson, and Georgia's sole Federalist representative also voted for him, giving him eight states.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The Vermont delegation was evenly split and cast a blank ballot.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The remaining state, Maryland, had five Federalist representatives to three Democratic-Republicans; one of its Federalist representatives voted for Jefferson, forcing that state delegation also to cast a blank ballot.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Publicly, Burr remained quiet between mid-December 1800 and mid-February 1801, when the electoral votes were counted.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Behind the scenes, he faced mounting pressure from within the party to step aside if he and Jefferson should tie in electoral votes.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Regardless, he refused to disavow the presidency, writing in December 1800 to Representative Samuel Smith (R-MD) that he would not "engage to resign" if chosen president, adding that the question was "unnecessary, unreasonable and impertinent".
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Rumors circulated that Representative James A.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Bayard (F-DE) had—purportedly in Burr's name—approached Smith and Edward Livingston (R-NY) with offers of political appointments if they voted for Burr.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Neither came to pass, however, chiefly due to Hamilton's energetic opposition to Burr.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton embarked on a frenzied letter-writing campaign to get Federalist Representatives to support Jefferson because he was "by far not so dangerous a man" as Burr; in short, he would much rather have someone with wrong principles than someone devoid of any.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] From February 11 to 17, the House cast a total of 35 ballots; each time eight state delegations voted for Jefferson, one short of the necessary majority of nine.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] On February 17, on the 36th ballot, Bayard changed his vote from Burr to no selection, joined by his allies in Maryland and Vermont.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] This changed the Maryland and Vermont votes from no selection to Jefferson, giving him the votes of 10 states and the presidency.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The four representatives present from South Carolina, all Federalists, also changed their 3–1 selection of Burr to four abstentions.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Due to the experiences of this and the previous election, sentiment for a new way of selecting the president and vice president rose significantly, resulting in the Twelfth Amendment.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] In the 2015 musical *Hamilton* by Lin Manuel Miranda, the contest between Jefferson and Burr is recounted in "The Election of 1800".
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The song focuses on Alexander Hamilton's role in deciding the outcome of the 1801 contingent election.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] The musical simplifies the complicated multiple elections somewhat, portraying Adams's unpopularity as making the real choice between Jefferson and Burr.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] Historians wrote that Adams did not lose that badly in the original election, with the musical inflating the size of Jefferson's victory.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1800-united-states-presidential-election] It implies Hamilton's support for Jefferson over Burr was the catalyst for the Burr–Hamilton duel; in fact, while that helped sour relations between Burr and Hamilton, the duel was ultimately provoked by Hamilton's statements about Burr in the 1804 New York gubernatorial election.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1801-state-of-the-union-address] The **1801 State of the Union Address** was written by Thomas Jefferson, the third president of the United States, on December 8, 1801.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1801-state-of-the-union-address] It was his first annual address and presented in Washington, D.C.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1801-state-of-the-union-address] He did not speak it to the 7th United States Congress because he thought that would make him seem like a king.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1801-state-of-the-union-address] Notably, the President commented on the hostilities that existed with the Barbary States, in which Barbary Pirates were attacking US commerce ships.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 1 to December 4, 1804.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican Party's ticket of incumbent president Thomas Jefferson and former New York governor George Clinton defeated the Federalist Party's ticket of former U.S. minister to France Charles Cotesworth Pinckney and former U.S. minister to the United Kingdom Rufus King.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] This was the first election held under the Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution, which required separate ballots for president and vice president.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson was unanimously renominated by his party's congressional nominating caucus in February; the caucus selected Clinton to succeed the outgoing vice president, Aaron Burr.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] A "semisecret" Federalist caucus elevated Pinckney and King as the party's national candidates; while news of the caucus was widely circulated, in states where electors were chosen by popular vote, the Federalist ticket was formally unpledged.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists in several states chose not to nominate electors, resulting in a lopsided popular vote margin for Jefferson.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson was widely popular and considered unbeatable by many observers, following his narrow election four years earlier.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Economic prosperity, the expansion of voting rights, and the disorganized state of the opposition all benefited his campaign.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists portrayed Jefferson as a demagogue for his embrace of populist, democratic politics, and a dictator for his use of patronage and reforms to the federal judiciary.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's complicity in slavery did little to damage his candidacy even in New England, where he carried the Federalist stronghold of Massachusetts.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson won the election in a landslide, carrying every state and all but two electoral districts where electors were chosen by popular vote.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney received the electoral votes of Connecticut and Delaware, where electors were appointed by the legislature, and two votes from unpledged electors in Maryland.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson polled more than 106,000 popular votes, representing 73 percent of the total, compared with fewer than 40,000 votes for the Federalist electors.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent Federalist president John Adams sought re-election in 1800, but was defeated by Democratic-Republican challenger Thomas Jefferson.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's running mate, Aaron Burr, was elected vice president following a contingent election in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The right to vote was widespread in the United States during the Early Republic, including the large majority of adult white men.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The expansion of voting rights during Jefferson's first term included the establishment of universal white male suffrage in Maryland in 1801.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Propertied, single women retained the right to vote in New Jersey, while Black men who met all other property and taxpaying requirements were eligible in New England, New Jersey, New York, North Carolina, Pennsylvania, and Tennessee.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In most places, voting was by secret ballot.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] (Kentucky and Virginia retained the English custom of oral voting.) Eligible individuals voted using paper tickets, typically handwritten, listing the voter's choice for the various offices.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Enforcement of property and taxpaying qualifications was generally lax, in part due to the frequency of land sales, which outpaced officials' ability to keep accurate records of ownership.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In other cases, local opinion or the threat of rioting might compel election officials to permit veterans and small landholders to vote when otherwise disenfranchised by state law.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Congress passed the Twelfth Amendment to the United States Constitution, which was ratified by the states prior to the election.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Amendment instructed the United States Electoral College to elect the president and vice president on separate ballots.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists opposed ratifying the Amendment, hoping to exploit the original electoral system to sow discord in the Democratic-Republican ranks.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] During the campaign, some Federalists encouraged the Democratic-Republican electors from New York to support Clinton for president over Jefferson.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Efforts to delay ratification of the Amendment were unsuccessful, and the new system took effect in September 1804 in time for the election.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson faced no internal opposition to his bid for re-election; the Democratic-Republican congressional caucus nominated him unanimously on February 25.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] With Burr out of the running, the selection of the vice-presidential candidate was the caucus's main responsibility.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] George Clinton and John Breckinridge were the leading contenders for the vice presidential nomination.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton had served as governor of New York for most of the last thirty years and was a veteran of the American Revolutionary War; he had received 50 electoral votes in the 1792 United States presidential election, and declined a place on the Democratic-Republican ticket in 1800.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Although of advanced age, his political views aligned with Jefferson's, and he remained popular with Democratic-Republicans in his home state.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Breckinridge, a Kentuckian, was the choice of Western Democratic-Republicans concerned with regional representation.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Other candidates included the U.S. attorney general, Levi Lincoln Sr.; the former U.S. senator from New Hampshire, John Langdon; and the U.S. postmaster general, Gideon Granger.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Thomas McKean was discussed as a possible contender, but withdrew prior to the caucus.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The caucus was attended by 110 Democratic-Republican members of Congress.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton won the nomination with 67 votes.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Congressional Federalists did not meet formally to nominate a ticket, as they had done in the previous election.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The party was ill-prepared to mount a national campaign, and few believed Jefferson could be defeated.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Instead, a "semisecret caucus" in Washington proposed Pinckney and King as the party's national candidates on February 22.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Although this meeting was widely reported, significant uncertainty persisted concerning the identities of the Federalist candidates throughout the campaign.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In states where electors were chosen by popular vote, the Federalist electors remained formally unpledged.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans established a vast network of state, county, town, and ward committees to conduct the campaign.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In states such as Ohio, the overriding importance of the presidential election was an agent of party unity.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic-Republicans organized celebrations to commemorate the anniversary of Jefferson's first inauguration on March 4 and the Louisiana Purchase on May 11.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Parades, dinners, and toasting were the mainstays of such events.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Supporters sang campaign songs such as "Jefferson and Liberty," written to commemorate the last election.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic-Republican militia units, professional associations, benevolent societies, and partisan groups like the Young Men of Democratic Principles were visible supporters of the president's re-election campaign.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republicans made effective use of the partisan press.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The party's national paper, the *National Intelligencer*, was widely circulated and supported a vast array of state and local print publications.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican campaign catered to the nation's developing white male democracy.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The abandonment of property requirements for voting in Maryland and New Jersey benefited Jefferson, whose economic policies were considered favorable to working people.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Democratic-Republican newspapers and broadsides were written in plain language accessible to the average person.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The themes of "simplicity and frugality" and equality of opportunity were central to the party's appeal to voters, contrasted against Federalist elitism.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In contrast to the Democratic-Republicans, the Federalists entered the campaign demoralized and to some degree leaderless.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney displayed little interest in the election and devoted most of 1804 to a local campaign against dueling.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The party lost its most influential leader in July, when Alexander Hamilton was killed in a duel by the outgoing vice president, Burr.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Hamilton's former deputy, Timothy Pickering, saw no hope for the presidential election and instead advocated for New England to secede from the United States.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Other Federalists simply withdrew from politics rather than endure a seemingly inevitable defeat.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Bayard, advocated for the party to update its tactics.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The growth of mass politics in the early nineteenth century made the Federalists' reliance on elite relationships increasingly obsolete.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists held celebrations on the anniversary of Washington's birthday and organized groups like the Washington Benevolent Societies.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The effectiveness of the party press was hindered by the stilted, formal style of many Federalist newspapers.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Criticism of Jefferson, rather than enthusiasm for Pinckney, characterized the Federalist campaign.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In states where the party nominated electors, its ticket was formally unpledged.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist press generally avoided mention of Pinckney and King; the Boston *Columbian Centinel* denied that the Federalist electors were pledged to Pinckney.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Dauer argues that the uncertainty surrounding the Federalist ticket cost the party the electoral votes of Massachusetts.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists described Jefferson as an aspiring dictator.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] They compared the Louisiana Purchase to Napoleon's European conquests and accused Jefferson of violating the Constitution, which did not specify the president's power to acquire new territory.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Increasingly, Federalists saw parallels between Jefferson's administration and the rule of European tyrants, including Napoleon, Maximilien Robespierre, and Julius Caesar.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's use of patronage and the impeachment of Samuel Chase by the House of Representatives in March 1804 were criticized by Federalists who feared Jefferson's growing influence over the political system.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The repeal of the Midnight Judges Act and the reduction of the United States Armed Forces were cast as attempts to dismantle the federal government of the United States.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's sexual relationship with Sally Hemings, an enslaved woman and the half-sister of his late wife, Martha Jefferson, was first exposed by James T.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson had six children with Hemings between 1795 and 1808, although some historians argue their relationship began much earlier, during Jefferson's tenure as the U.S. minister to France.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists seized on the scandal to attack Jefferson's hypocrisy and personal character.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Partisan journals printed doggerel mocking Jefferson's promiscuity with verses that emphasized Hemings's race and complexion.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In pillorying Jefferson as an enslaver, Federalist writers did not intend to critique social inequality; instead, they sought to use Jefferson's complicity in slavery to discredit democratic politics.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists attacked Jefferson's religious views, which they described as atheism.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalist ministers characterized the Democratic-Republican Party as a grave threat to Christianity.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson's economic policies catered to the interests of free men and entrepreneurs, in contrast to Federalist policies that prioritized wealthy creditors.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Joyce Appleby argues that Jefferson's laissez-faire posture facilitated commercial expansion that benefited white men regardless of class.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Whereas the Federalists used economic regulation to promote the interests of creditors, Democratic-Republicans favored a decentralized economy in which opportunities to participate in commerce were more broadly accessible.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists interpreted Democratic-Republican policies as an attack on elite privilege and defended the principle of economic inequality.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Although many Democratic-Republicans were skeptical of national corporations, corporations and banks flourished at the state and local level.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Both Jefferson and Pinckney were enslavers.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney played a critical role in the adoption of the Three-Fifths Clause by the Constitutional Convention and opposed the efforts to end the Atlantic slave trade.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson criticized slavery in print, but did little either privately or politically to diminish it; as president, he withheld diplomatic recognition from the First Empire of Haiti, the first independent state in the Americas established as the result of a successful slave rebellion.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists attempted to make slavery an issue in New England, with limited success.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Both national parties sought to avoid discussion of slavery during the 1790s; after 1801, the decline of the Federalist Party in the Southern United States freed Northern Federalists to attack slavery more directly.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Antislavery rhetoric featured in some Federalists' critiques of the Louisiana Purchase.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] New England Federalists demanded the repeal of the Three-Fifths Clause, which disadvantaged the region in terms of congressional apportionment.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] These appeals largely failed to motivate opposition to Jefferson, while accompanying calls for secession met with little popular support.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Criticism of the Three-Fifths Clause emphasized New England Federalists' partisan self-interest.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Many Federalists blamed this provision for their defeat in the last election.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Fisher Ames wrote that "black votes" had elected Jefferson in 1800 and that the administration therefore lacked a popular mandate.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] New England Federalists frequently pointed to prominent Democratic-Republicans' complicity in slavery as evidence of the party's hypocrisy.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Opposing political rights for both white and Black workers, they pointed to the contradictions in Jeffersonian democracy as proof that a political system based on mass participation was unworkable.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson won the election in a landslide, carrying every state and all but two districts where electors were chosen by popular vote.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists appeared to win the popular vote on Election Day in North Carolina's Fayetteville district, but the exclusion of the return from Montgomery County, North Carolina, subsequently gave the district's single electoral vote to Jefferson.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson carried Massachusetts and New Hampshire, as well as seven of nine Maryland districts.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In Pennsylvania, Jefferson carried every county except Adams, where a last-minute Federalist effort narrowly succeeded in keeping the county out of the Democratic-Republican column.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Ohio Federalists' attempt to split the Democratic-Republican Party was unsuccessful, and the Jefferson electors defeated the Federalist ticket by a wide margin.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalists did not contest the remaining popular vote states, but unpledged electors received write-in votes in New Jersey and Virginia.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Pinckney received electoral votes from Connecticut and Delaware, where electors were chosen by the state legislature, while Jefferson swept the remaining states for a total of 162 electoral votes.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] As of 2024, Jefferson was the first of eight presidential nominees to win a significant number of electoral votes in at least three elections, the others being Henry Clay, Andrew Jackson, Grover Cleveland, William Jennings Bryan, Franklin D.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Roosevelt, Richard Nixon, and Donald Trump.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Of these, Jackson, Cleveland, and Roosevelt also won the popular vote in at least three elections.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Jefferson, Cleveland, Roosevelt, and Trump were also their respective party's nominees for three consecutive elections.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] Nineteenth-century election laws required voters to elect the members of the Electoral College individually, rather than as a block.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] This sometimes resulted in small differences in the number of votes cast for electors pledged to the same presidential nominee, if some voters did not vote for all the electors nominated by a party.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In most cases, this table compares the votes for the most popular elector on each ticket.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In the single-member districts in Maryland, North Carolina, and Tennessee, the result is the sum of all votes for electors pledged to one nominee.
[src:1804-united-states-presidential-election/1804-united-states-presidential-election] In Virginia, where several distinct anti-Jefferson tickets ran in different parts of the state, the result shown is the sum of the votes for the leading electors in each county.
